               <history>
                  <origin>Completed by <persName key="person_f5107" role="scr" change="#role-assignment" xml:lang="fa-Latn-x-lc">Ḥusayn bin Ḥasan</persName>, probably in the <origPlace ref="http://vocab.getty.edu/page/tgn/7000208" key="place_7000208">Indian subcontinent</origPlace>; undated, but possibly <date cert="medium" calendar="#Gregorian" notBefore="1600" notAfter="1700">17th century</date>.</origin>
                  <provenance><p>The acquisition of the manuscript in India and its arrival in Britain and division into four volumes remains unclear.</p></provenance>
                  <provenance><p>Subsequently acquired by Methodist minister <persName
                     role="fmo ins" key="person_120696480"
                     ref="https://viaf.org/viaf/120696480/">Rev. Adam Clarke
                     (1762–1832)</persName>, after whose death his son <persName role="fmo"
                        key="person_79253656" ref="https://viaf.org/viaf/79253656/">Jospeh
                        Butterworth Bulmer Clarke (d. 1855)</persName> inherited the volume and
                     describes its present state in a catalogue published in <date
                        calendar="#Gregorian" when="1835">1835</date>.</p></provenance>
                  <provenance><p>The next year on <date calendar="#Gregorian" when="1836-06-20">20 June
                     1836</date>, Clarke's son auctioned his father's collection
                     through the <placeName ref="http://vocab.getty.edu/page/tgn/7011781" key="place_7011781">London</placeName> firm of <persName role="auc"
                        ref="http://viaf.org/viaf/133731879" key="person_133731879">Sotheby &amp;
                        Son</persName> where bookseller <persName role="bsl"
                           ref="http://viaf.org/viaf/69276015" key="person_69276015">John George Cochrane (1780–1852)</persName> purchased the set for £3 19 shillings.</p></provenance>
                  <provenance><p>Probably from Cochrane by scholar <persName type="standard" role="fmo"
                     ref="http://viaf.org/viaf/20108923/" key="person_20108923">Nathaniel
                     Bland (1803–1865)</persName> for his library at Randalls Park, <placeName ref="http://vocab.getty.edu/page/tgn/7011735" key="place_7011735">Leatherhead</placeName>. After his death, <placeName ref="http://vocab.getty.edu/page/tgn/7011781" key="place_7011781">London</placeName> bookseller <persName type="standard" role="bsl"
                        ref="http://viaf.org/viaf/5679225/" key="person_5679225">Bernard Quaritch
                        (1819–1899)</persName> sold his oriental
                     manuscripts to <persName type="standard" role="fmo"
                        ref="http://viaf.org/viaf/97751058/" key="person_97751058">Alexander
                        Lindsay, 25th Earl of Crawford (1812–1880)</persName> in <date calendar="#Gregorian" when="1866"
                           >1866</date>, and moved to <orgName ref="http://viaf.org/viaf/295427552" key="person_295427552">Bibliotheca Lindesiana</orgName> at Haigh Hall, <placeName ref="http://vocab.getty.edu/page/tgn/7010384" key="place_7010384">Wigan</placeName>.</p>
                  </provenance>
                  <provenance><p>Purchased by <persName type="standard" role="dnr" key="person_f6379" change="#prov-markup"
                     >Enriqueta Rylands (1843–1908)</persName> in <date calendar="#Gregorian"
                        when="1901">1901</date> from <persName type="standard" role="fmo"
                           ref="http://viaf.org/viaf/9985420/" key="person_9985420">James Ludovic
                           Lindsay, 26th Earl of Crawford (1847–1913)</persName>.</p></provenance>
                  <acquisition>
                     <p>Bequeathed by <persName type="standard" key="person_f6379" change="#prov-markup">Enriqueta Rylands
                        (1843–1908)</persName> in <date calendar="#Gregorian" when="1908"
                           >1908</date> to the <orgName type="corporation" role="rps"
                              ref="http://viaf.org/viaf/312795145/">John Rylands
                              Library</orgName>, <placeName>Manchester</placeName>.</p>
                  </acquisition>
               </history>
